Investigation of A/B test data¶

Scenario:

  • Scenario here is that fresh text has been tried in Latam countries rather than just using the Spanish text, so they are in more vernacular style
  • The aim of this analysis on the test data is to see if this improved conversion or not

Makes use of:

  • T-test for comparison of the two sample means of the test and control groups
  • pymc3 for MCMC generation of posterior distributions of conversion rates for test and control groups

Key conclusions:

  • Uruguay and Argentina are highly over-represented in the test
  • Further, Uruguay and Argentina have lower conversion rates and so through this over-representation have a disproportionate effect on the overall conversion rate in the test
  • Once this is accounted for, for instance by just looking within countries, the difference in conversion rates is not statistically significant, and so there is insignificant evidence to conclude that the test has resulted in a change in conversion rate
  • To be sure, ideally would ask for the test to be re-run, with each country having very similar proportions within the test and control groups
  • The test has only been carried out over 5 days -- ideally a longer period would be used e.g. 2 weeks

In [13]:
# Is this difference statistically significant?
# null hypothesis that means are equal
# let's see what the p-values look like

print(
    stats.ttest_ind(
        df.loc[df.test == 1, 'conversion'], # Conversions in test
        df.loc[df.test == 0, 'conversion'], # Conversions in control
        equal_var=True # Assume equal population variance
    ),
    '\n',
    stats.ttest_ind(
        df.loc[df.test == 1, 'conversion'], # Conversions in test
        df.loc[df.test == 0, 'conversion'], # Conversions in control
        equal_var=False # Do not assume equal population variance
    )
)

# p-values are both very small so we can reject the null that the means are the same 
# => the means are different

# y = test; conversion is not relevent here
# the rest willb e dummified
df_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_curr.drop(columns=['conversion']))

X = df_dummies.copy(deep=True)
y = X.pop('test')
model = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight='balanced', # automatically adjust weights to reflect class frequencies
                               min_impurity_decrease=0.001, # don't split for the sake of it
                               random_state=0) # reproducability
model.fit(X, y) # Fit our model

# Let's add in p-values too so we can see what those look like

t_ = df.groupby('country')['conversion'].agg(
[
    ('p-value', lambda x: stats.ttest_ind(
        x[df["test"] == 1], 
        x[df["test"] == 0], 
        equal_var=False).pvalue),
    ('overall', lambda x: x.mean()),
    ('test', lambda x: x[df["test"] == 1].mean()),
    ('control', lambda x: x[df["test"] == 0].mean()),
], axis=1).sort_values(by='overall')

In [21]:
# Let's say we also want to take a Baysian approach using MCMC to make doubly sure
# (in reality the sizes are large enough for this example that classical/frequentist is fine)
#
# We are interested in:
#
# P(True conversion rate | Data) ~~ P(Data | True conversion rate) · P(True conversion rate)
# i.e.
# posterior ~~ liklihood · prior

# Converstion values
test_vals = df.loc[df["test"] == 1, 'conversion'].values
cont_vals = df.loc[df["test"] == 0, 'conversion'].values

# Observed values
n = len(test_vals) + len(cont_vals)
obs_test = (test_vals == 1).sum()
obs_cont = (cont_vals == 1).sum()

with pm.Model() as model: # Context management
    # Define priors -- flat distributions for each
    prior_test = pm.Uniform('prior_test', 0, 1)
    prior_cont = pm.Uniform('prior_cont', 0, 1)

    # Define likelihood -- binomial likelihoods, feeding in the priors and observed data for each
    like_test = pm.Binomial('like_test', n=n, p=prior_test, observed=obs_test) 
    like_cont = pm.Binomial('like_cont', n=n, p=prior_cont, observed=obs_cont)
    
    # Define metrics -- these are our differences between the two distibutions
    pm.Deterministic('difference', prior_test - prior_cont)
    pm.Deterministic('relation', (prior_test/prior_cont)-1)
    
    # Inference
    trace = pm.sample(draws=50000, step=pm.Metropolis(), start=pm.find_MAP(), progressbar=True)
In [23]:
# View traces
# We do not show first 2k traces by convention as these can be noisey

# As above though when we look at an individual country the result will be different
pm.plot_posterior(trace[2000:], varnames=['difference', 'relation'], 
                      ref_val=0, color='#87ceeb');

# Mexico had the smallest p-value above so let's check that one -- we could also do on 
# country by country basis for the whole list if we wished

# Converstion values
test_vals = df.loc[(df["test"] == 1) & (df["country"] == 'Mexico'), 'conversion'].values
cont_vals = df.loc[(df["test"] == 0) & (df["country"] == 'Mexico'), 'conversion'].values

# Observed values
n = len(test_vals) + len(cont_vals)
obs_test = (test_vals == 1).sum()
obs_cont = (cont_vals == 1).sum()

    prior_test = pm.Uniform('prior_test', 0, 1)
    prior_cont = pm.Uniform('prior_cont', 0, 1)

    # Define likelihood -- binomial likelihoods, feeding in the priors and the observed data for each
    like_test = pm.Binomial('like_test', n=n, p=prior_test, observed=obs_test) 
    like_cont = pm.Binomial('like_cont', n=n, p=prior_cont, observed=obs_cont)
    
    # Define metrics -- these are our differences between the two distibutions

    pm.Deterministic('relation', (prior_test/prior_cont)-1)
    
    # Inference
